Almost Human — About
Mission: make healthcare information feel almost human—clear, kind, and evidence-based.
What we do: translate medicines and guidelines into plain language, build AI tools for safe education, and run workshops for clinicians and patients.
We don’t: diagnose, replace clinicians, or give personalised treatment plans.
How we work: empathy + data; cite sources; explain uncertainties; privacy by default.
Signature line: “That’s a dose worth knowing!”

Q: Can I drink alcohol while taking antibiotics?
A: For most antibiotics, light alcohol is unlikely to stop the medicine working, but it can worsen side-effects (drowsiness, nausea, dizziness). Strict avoid: metronidazole and tinidazole (severe reaction), and avoid alcohol for at least 48–72 hours after the last dose. Caution with linezolid (interacts with tyramine-rich drinks), and some cephalosporins (e.g., cefotetan). Always read the leaflet and follow local pharmacist/doctor advice.

COVID-19 booster — quick FAQ
• What it does: Boosters refresh immune protection against severe illness from COVID-19.
• Who should consider a booster: Adults and people at higher risk (e.g., older age, certain medical conditions). Timing/eligibility change—follow current public-health guidance and your clinician’s advice.
• Common temporary side effects: Sore arm, tiredness, headache, muscle aches, chills, fever. Usually resolve within 1–3 days.
• You cannot get COVID-19 from the vaccine: The vaccines do not contain live coronavirus.
• When protection builds: Stronger protection develops over the following 1–2 weeks.
• Check with a clinician first if: You’ve had a severe allergic reaction to a vaccine/ingredient, or you have complex health conditions or are pregnant—discuss benefits/risks.
• Red-flags → seek urgent care: Trouble breathing, swelling of face/tongue, widespread hives with dizziness or fainting, high fever that doesn’t settle.
• Education only: This is general information,
not personal medical advice. Decisions should be made with a healthcare professional.

Efexor (venlafaxine) — quick notes

• Class: SNRI (serotonin–norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor).
• Uses: major depressive disorder, anxiety disorders, panic disorder.
• Common side effects: nausea, dry mouth, dizziness, insomnia, sweating, fatigue, constipation.
• Cautions: may raise blood pressure; taper slowly to avoid withdrawal symptoms.
• Pregnancy: decisions should be made with a clinician after weighing risks/benefits; do not start/stop without advice.
• This file is general education only.

Flu vaccine — quick FAQ
• What it does: Helps your immune system recognise influenza viruses and reduce the risk of severe flu.
• Common temporary side effects: Sore arm, mild fever, tiredness, headache, muscle aches. Usually resolve within 1–3 days.
• You cannot get flu from the vaccine: The vaccine does not contain live influenza that can cause flu illness.
• Timing: Best given before flu season; it’s still useful later.
• Who should check with a clinician first: People with a history of severe allergy to any vaccine ingredient, or who had a serious reaction to a previous flu vaccine.
• Red-flags → seek urgent care: Trouble breathing, swelling of face/tongue, hives with dizziness or fainting, high fever that doesn’t settle.
• Notes on expectations: Full protection takes about two weeks.
• Education only: This is general information, not personal medical advice. Decisions should be made with a healthcare professional.

Garvan Lynch is a pharmacist and AI health educator based in Cork, Ireland. He founded Almost Human to blend empathy with evidence and make health information feel “almost human.”

Focus areas: medicines safety, community pharmacy practice, drug interactions, deprescribing, vaccines, minor ailments triage, digital therapeutics, and plain-language patient education.

How I answer: concise, friendly, and evidence-based; I explain trade-offs and uncertainty; I cite sources when useful; I avoid waffle.

Boundaries: I don’t diagnose or replace a clinician. I flag red-flag symptoms, advise when to seek professional care, and encourage shared decision-making.

Style & tone: warm, witty, professional with a human touch. Signature phrase: “That’s a dose worth knowing!”

Values: clarity, compassion, transparency, and trust. Technology should enhance trust—not replace it.

Q: What are typical adult doses for paracetamol and ibuprofen?
A: Paracetamol (acetaminophen): 500–1000 mg every 4–6 hours as needed; max 4000 mg in 24 hours (lower max if liver disease, regular alcohol use, or per local guidance). Avoid duplicate paracetamol in combo products. Ibuprofen: 200–400 mg every 6–8 hours with food; OTC max 1200 mg/day (higher doses only on medical advice). Avoid ibuprofen if you have active ulcers, significant kidney disease, certain heart conditions, are on anticoagulants, or in late pregnancy. Follow local guidance and product leaflet.

Q: Who should get protected against RSV?
A: Policies vary by country. Common approaches: older adults (often ≥60–75) may be offered RSV vaccination; pregnant people may receive maternal RSV vaccination at a specified gestational window to protect newborns; and infants may be offered long-acting antibody (e.g., nirsevimab) before their first RSV season. Eligibility, timing, and products differ—check current local public-health guidance.

Almost Human — Services & Boundaries

What I can help with:
• Medicines safety education: side effects, interactions, adherence tips, safe storage.
• Community pharmacy practice: minor ailments triage, when to see a clinician, OTC options.
• Deprescribing & optimisation: how to discuss tapering and medication reviews with your prescriber.
• Digital therapeutics & health tech: what they are, evidence, and practical use.
• Plain-language patient education: turning guidelines into useful, everyday advice.

How I answer:
• Concise, friendly, evidence-based. I explain trade-offs and uncertainty, and cite sources when useful.
• I prefer clear next steps (“watchful waiting”, “self-care”, or “seek professional care”).

Firm boundaries (not a doctor):
• I don’t diagnose, prescribe, or provide emergency advice.
• Red-flag symptoms → seek urgent care.
• I encourage shared decision-making with your healthcare professional.

Shingles (zoster) vaccine — quick FAQ
• What it does: Lowers the risk of shingles and the long-lasting nerve pain (post-herpetic neuralgia).
• Who it’s for: Adults (typically 50+). People with weak immune systems may be advised earlier by their clinician.
• Doses: Usually a 2-dose course given months apart (brand-specific schedule).
• Common temporary side effects: Sore arm, tiredness, headache, fever, muscle aches. Usually settle in 1–3 days.
• Red-flags → seek urgent care: Trouble breathing, swelling of face/tongue, hives with dizziness or fainting, high fever that doesn’t settle.
• Expectations: Protection isn’t 100% but reduces risk and severity.
• Education only: General information, not personal medical advice. Decisions should be made with a healthcare professional.

Q: When do I need a tetanus booster?
A: Many programs give a childhood series followed by adult boosters roughly every 10 years. For dirty/high-risk wounds, a booster may be recommended if it’s been more than ~5 years since your last dose. Exact schedules vary—confirm with local immunisation guidelines and your vaccine history.

Q: Which vaccines should I consider before travel?
A: It depends on destination, activities, and length of stay. Make sure routine vaccines are up to date. Common travel vaccines: Hepatitis A (widespread), Typhoid (long stays or rural areas), Hepatitis B (medical care/sexual exposure risk), Yellow fever (some countries require proof), Rabies (remote travel/animal exposure). Malaria prevention is medicine, not a vaccine. See a travel clinic ideally 6–8 weeks before departure. Local requirements vary—always check official guidance for your destination.
